<p>A significant number of network calls from web pages are merely for statistics.</p>  <p>The most widely used practice is a GET/POST request with header or URL parameters about the state being tracked.</p>  <p>Can someone explain why this is done with HTTP and not UDP?</p>  <ul> <li>There is nothing actionable if the tracking GET/POST fails.</li> <li>Using HTTP means waiting for a useless response.  Granted modern browsers reduce the pain somewhat by having a small pool of outstanding requests, but ... why?</li> </ul>